		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
				<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Assignment 5</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From cs54:  Introduction to Robotics</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>Assignment 5 is due Tuesday at 1:59 pm.  Submit your code, drawn figures, and discussion notes by e-mail to Weifu and me as usual.  During class on Tuesday, I'll ask you to demonstrate your solution for problems 6 and 7.
</p><p>The first two problems require you to draw pictures, and are a warmup based on lecture.  Please draw your pictures using a vector graphics program (Inkscape would be fine) and save as .eps or .svg.  In the remaining problems, you will use a desktop or laptop computer to remotely control an iRobot Create over a bluetooth connection.  You will write programs to move the Create in different patterns, and conduct experiments to measure the accuracy of the robot motions and encoders.
</p><p>You may use your own computer if you have bluetooth capabilities, or you can use one of the iMacs already in the lab. The "create manager" link to the left has some information you'll want to get the robots running, and Weifu and I stand ready to answer your questions.
</p><p>There are five iRobot Creates with Element Direct bluetooth modems in the robotics lab. 
</p><p>The first thing you'll need to do is to connect the bluetooth in the imac to a robot.  On a mac, you'll use the Bluetooth setup assistant.  After you pair with the "element serial" device, you'll have a device file with a name something like "/dev/tty.ElementSerial".  When you've found this file, pass this filename as a string to the constructor for the Createmanager object.  
</p><p>Confusingly, all of the bluetooth devices are called the same thing on the mac, "element serial".  If you have trouble with figuring out whether you've managed to connect to the robot you intended to, you can use the bluetooth preferences to find out which hardware bluetooth address you actually managed to connect with.  Hardware addresses are printed on tape attached to the front of each BAM device.
</p><p><br />
</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents"><tr><td><div id="toctitle"><h2>Contents</h2></div>
