<a name="Problem_1:__Configuration-space_visualization" id="Problem_1:__Configuration-space_visualization"></a><h2> <span class="mw-headline"> Problem 1:  Configuration-space visualization </span></h2>
<p>Draw a rough floorplan of the room you are sitting in, complete with furniture and other obstacles.  Draw a triangular robot.  Assume the robot can translate and rotate, and attach a frame to the robot; let the configuration space be parameterized by the location and orientation of that frame <span class="texhtml"><i>q</i> = (<i>x</i>,<i>y</i>,&theta;)</span> with respect to some world frame.  Draw the slice of configuration space with <span class="texhtml">&theta; = 0</span>, and a slice of configuration space with <span class="texhtml">&theta; = &pi; / 4</span>.
</p>
<a name="Problem_2:__Workspace_for_a_planar_2R_arm" id="Problem_2:__Workspace_for_a_planar_2R_arm"></a><h2> <span class="mw-headline"> Problem 2:  Workspace for a planar 2R arm </span></h2>
<p>Consider a planar 2R arm, with first link of length 4, second link of length 2.  (Links are counted from the immovable base.)  There are also joint limits.  The first joint has a range from 0 to 180 degrees, and the second joint has a range from -45 to 45.  Draw the reachable workspace of the end effector for this arm. 
</p>
<a name="Problem_3:__drive_forwards.2C_turn_degrees.2C_and_drive_square" id="Problem_3:__drive_forwards.2C_turn_degrees.2C_and_drive_square"></a><h2> <span class="mw-headline"> Problem 3:  drive_forwards, turn_degrees, and drive_square </span></h2>
<p>Write a function drive_forwards(double cm) to drive the robot forwards a distance specified in centimeters.  You will use the encoders to tell how far the robot has driven.  
</p><p>Notice that there are some problems with the encoders -- they don't give an accurate reading unless the speed is carefully tuned.  Run some experiments to determine how accurate your method and robot are, and tune the speeds until you can get results that are accurate to within about one centimeter.
</p><p>Now write a turn_degrees(int deg) function to turn the robot in place clockwise (negative value for deg) or counterclockwise (positive deg) some number of degrees.  Test your function and tune as needed.
</p><p>Finally, write a method to cause the robot to drive in a square.  Write a one-paragraph discussion of your results for this problem.
</p>
<a name="Problem_4:__navigate_deadreckoning" id="Problem_4:__navigate_deadreckoning"></a><h2> <span class="mw-headline"> Problem 4:  navigate_deadreckoning </span></h2>
<p>Write a function navigate_blind() to cause the robot to navigate the maze laid out in the robot lab.  Do not use any sensors other than the wheel encoders, which estimate where the robot is using the number of times the wheels have turned.
</p><p>Assume you know the shape of the maze and the starting configuration for the robot.
</p>
<a name="Problem_5:__move_until_bump_and_navigate_with_bump" id="Problem_5:__move_until_bump_and_navigate_with_bump"></a><h2> <span class="mw-headline"> Problem 5:  move_until_bump and navigate_with_bump </span></h2>
<p>Write a function move_until_bump() that causes the robot to drive until the bump sensors are triggered.  move_until_bump() can be used to remove translational error in the robot position -- the robot executes a move_until_bump(), and then moves back to the center of the grid square.  Write a navigate_with_bump() function to navigate the maze in this way.
</p>
<a name="Problem_6:__line_follower" id="Problem_6:__line_follower"></a><h2> <span class="mw-headline"> Problem 6:  line_follower </span></h2>
<p>There is a curved duct-tape path around the outside of the maze.  Write a program that uses the IR cliff-sensors to follow the duct-tape curve.  The program should be both fast and reliable!
</p>
<a name="Problem_7:__maze_navigation_with_A.2A" id="Problem_7:__maze_navigation_with_A.2A"></a><h2> <span class="mw-headline"> Problem 7:  maze navigation with A* </span></h2>
<p>Use the A* algorithm you wrote last week for navigating a maze, together with "navigate_until_bump" to allow the robot to move between any two specified locations in the maze.
</p>
<a name="Extra_credit" id="Extra_credit"></a><h2> <span class="mw-headline"> Extra credit </span></h2>
<p>Implement your blind-robot motion algorithm from the previous assignment on the robot.  
</p>
<a name="Create_notes" id="Create_notes"></a><h2> <span class="mw-headline"> Create notes </span></h2>
<p>A few hints.  
</p><p>Problem 6 asks you to write a program to follow the line.  Over the black metal floor, the cliff sensor returns a value of a few hundred.  Over shiny tape, the number is closer to 3000.  If you lift the robot up, it will give a sensor value of 0 (since no IR light it being reflected back).
</p>
